 the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish:  see  Hetherington  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hetherington","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from Hetherington in Wark (Northumberland) or from Harrington (Northamptonshire), both from the Old English personal name <i>Hǣthhere</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. This surname has been established in Ireland (Laois, Tyrone) since the 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda de Hecherton was born in 1258, in Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Gilbert de Hecherton, was 27 and her mother, Unknown, was 23. She married John de Southwell I in 1279, in Nottinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1258–":"1258–Surnud","1258–Female":"1258–Surnud","1249–Male":"1249–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1282–Male":"1282–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1232–Male":"1232–Surnud","1236–Female":"1236–Surnud","1249":"1249","1258":"1258","Abt 1282":"umbes 1282","1236":"1236","1279":"1279","1232":"1232","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","Hecherton near Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Southwell, , Nottingham, England":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1258–":"1258–Kuollut","1258–Female":"1258–Kuollut","1249–Male":"1249–Kuollut","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1282–Male":"1282–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1232–Male":"1232–Kuollut","1236–Female":"1236–Kuollut","1249":"1249","1258":"1258","Abt 1282":"noin 1282","1236":"1236","1279":"1279","1232":"1232","1282":"1282","1280":"1280","Hecherton near Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Southwell, , Nottingham, England":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, Engla